SIMPLE: solitude
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Solitude
<hw>Sol"i*tude</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., from L.
<ets>solitudo</ets>, <ets>solus</ets> alone. See <er>Sole</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>state of being alone, or withdrawn
from society; a lonely life; loneliness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whosoever is delighted with <qex>solitude</qex> is either a wild
beast or a god.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O <qex>Solitude</qex>! where are the charms⟦br⟧
That sages have seen in thy face?</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Remoteness from society; destitution of company;
seclusion; -- said of places; <as>as, the <ex>solitude</ex> of a
wood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>solitude</qex> of his little parish is become matter of
great comfort to him.</q> <rj><qau>Law.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>solitary or lonely place; a desert or
wilderness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In these deep <qex>solitudes</qex> and awful cells⟦br⟧
Where heavenly pensive contemplation dwells.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> Loneliness; soitariness; loneness; retiredness;
recluseness. -- <er>Solitude</er>, <er>Retirement</er>,
<er>Seclusion</er>, <er>Loneliness</er>.</syn>
<usage><xex>Retirement</xex> is a withdrawal from general society,
implying that a person has been engaged in its scenes.
<xex>Solitude</xex> describes the fact that a person is alone;
<xex>seclusion</xex>, that he is shut out from others, usually by his
own choice; <xex>loneliness</xex>, that he feels the pain and oppression
of being alone. Hence, <xex>retirement</xex> is opposed to a gay,
active, or public life; <xex>solitude</xex>, to society;
<xex>seclusion</xex>, to freedom of access on the part of others; and
<xex>loneliness</xex>, enjoyment of that society which the heart
demands.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O blest <qex>retirement</qex>, friend to life's decline.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such only can enjoy the country who are capable of thinking when
they are there; then they are prepared for <qex>solitude</qex>; and in
that [the country] <qex>solitude</qex> is prepared for them.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is a place of <qex>seclusion</qex> from the external world.</q>
<rj><qau>Bp. Horsley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These evils . . . seem likely to reduce it [a city] ere long to
the <qex>loneliness</qex> and the insignificance of a village.</q>
<rj><qau>Eustace.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solivagant</ent>⟦br⟧
